50|$|In late 2012, the ACLU {{announced}} {{a settlement in}} the case, under which police must now observe rigorous rules during <b>traffic</b> <b>stops</b> in Tenaha and Shelby County: <b>traffic</b> <b>stops</b> will be videotaped, and the officer must give reason for the stop and for suspicion of criminal activity. Drivers are to be advised that they can refuse a search, and dogs {{will no longer be}} used in conducting <b>traffic</b> <b>stops.</b> Property determined to have been taken improperly must be returned within 30 business days. Also, asset forfeiture revenue from <b>traffic</b> <b>stops</b> must be donated to non-profit organizations, or used to pay for the officer training required by the settlement.|$|R
